# Feature completeness — end-to-end proof

Never claim a feature “exists,” “works,” or “is complete” unless you can trace it end-to-end.

For **each** claimed feature, provide all twelve points with file/path evidence. If any point is missing, the feature is **INCOMPLETE**.

1. UI entry point (page path + button/control label)
2. API endpoint (`METHOD` + path)
3. Application service (file + method) — or explicitly “route-only / no application service”
4. Domain rule (file + symbol) — or “none — orchestration / service invariants only”
5. Repository used (interface / implementation)
6. Database tables modified (or “read-only”)
7. Audit events written (action strings) — or “none”
8. Notifications generated (types) — or “none”
9. Permission required (code) — or “authenticated only” / “public”
10. Unit/integration test covering it (file + test name) — or **MISSING**
11. Exact manual test steps
12. Expected result

## Rules

- Do not invent missing layers. Say **MISSING** or **INCOMPLETE**.
- Do not treat “code exists” as “complete” if tests, audits, or UI are absent where the product design requires them.
- Do not add out-of-scope seed users (e.g. Western Region) unless the stakeholder explicitly requests it.
- Prefer updating `docs/feature-e2e-proof.md` when correcting completeness claims.
- Staging evidence still belongs in `docs/staging-e2e-acceptance.md`.
